\section*{Self-Inflating Balloon}

\subsection*{Chemical Principle: Acid-Base Reaction}
When we mix vinegar (acetic acid) and baking soda (sodium bicarbonate), a chemical reaction occurs that produces \textbf{Carbon Dioxide ($CO_2$)} gas.

\subsection*{Chemical Equation}
The reaction between baking soda and vinegar is represented as:
\[ NaHCO_3 (s) + CH_3COOH (aq) \rightarrow CH_3COONa (aq) + H_2O (l) + CO_2 (g) \]

The $CO_2$ gas needs room to expand, so it escapes the bottle and enters the balloon, causing it to inflate.

\subsection*{Visual Demonstration}
\includegraphics[Animated GIF showing Chemical Reaction Inflating a Balloon]{https://res.cloudinary.com/liohnerd16/image/upload/v1778476208/science_projects/self_inflating_gif.gif}

\subsection*{Required Tools}
\begin{itemize}
    \item 1 rubber balloon.
    \item 1 empty plastic bottle (approx. 500ml).
    \item Vinegar.
    \item Baking Soda.
    \item Funnel (to pour powder into the balloon easily).
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Instructions}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Pour vinegar into about 1/3 of the plastic bottle.
    \item Use a funnel to pour about 2-3 spoonfuls of baking soda into the balloon.
    \item Carefully fit the neck of the balloon over the bottle opening (avoid dropping the powder yet).
    \item Lift the balloon to let the baking soda fall into the vinegar and watch the result!
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{Shopping Suggestions}
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline
Item & Suggested Place \\
\hline
Food-grade Baking Soda & Supermarket or Shopee \\
Colorful Balloons & Stationery store \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

