\section*{Biogas from Kitchen Waste}

\subsection*{Scientific Principle: Anaerobic Digestion}

The process of creating biogas is called \textbf{anaerobic digestion}. In an oxygen-free environment, anaerobic bacteria "eat" organic matter (like vegetable peels, food scraps) and release a gas mixture, primarily \textbf{Methane ($CH_4$)} and Carbon Dioxide ($CO_2$).

\subsection*{Detailed Biogas System Diagram}
\includegraphics[Technical Schematic of Anaerobic Biogas Digestion Plant]{/assets/images/projects/biogas-anaerobic-digestion-system.svg}


\subsection*{Biogas Composition}
The captured gas typically consists of:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Methane ($CH_4$)}: 50-75\% (The main component that provides energy for combustion).
    \item \textbf{Carbon Dioxide ($CO_2$)}: 25-50\%.
    \item Other gases (Nitrogen, Hydrogen, etc.): < 5\%.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Required Materials}
\begin{itemize}
    \item 1 large plastic container with a tight lid (approx. 20 liters).
    \item Plastic gas tubing (PVC or silicone).
    \item Gas storage bag (can use a tire inner tube or thick plastic bag).
    \item Organic waste (fruit peels, vegetables, leftover rice).
    \item Warm water.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Instructions}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Waste Processing}: Finely chop or blend kitchen waste to make it easier for bacteria to break down.
    \item \textbf{Mixing}: Mix waste with water in a 1:1 ratio to create a slurry.
    \item \textbf{Digestion}: Pour the mixture into the container, seal the lid tightly, and connect the gas tube to the storage bag.
    \item \textbf{Waiting}: Place the container in a warm area. After about 1-2 weeks, gas will start to produce and inflate the storage bag.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{Safety Warning}
Methane is flammable. Never test with fire near the digester system without professional guidance. Always perform the experiment in a well-ventilated area.

