\section*{DIY Soldering Iron from a Lighter — Thermal Conductivity}

\subsection*{Safety Warning}
\begin{center}
\textbf{WARNING: This project involves an open flame and high-temperature metal. Always work in a well-ventilated area and keep flammable materials away. Use pliers to handle hot components.}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Scientific Principle: Thermal Conductivity}
This project demonstrates how heat is transferred through solid materials. \textbf{Thermal conductivity} is the measure of a material's ability to conduct heat. 
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Copper}: Copper is used for the soldering tip because it has one of the highest thermal conductivities among common metals ($k \approx 401 \text{ W/m}\cdot\text{K}$). 
    \item \textbf{Heat Transfer}: When the lighter flame heats one end of the copper wire, the kinetic energy of the atoms increases, and this energy is passed along the wire until the entire tip is hot enough to melt solder.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Installation Diagram}
\includegraphics[Diagram of a DIY Soldering Iron using a lighter and copper wire]{data:image/svg+xml;base64,}

\subsection*{Materials Needed}
\begin{itemize}
    \item 1 standard butane lighter.
    \item 10-15cm of thick copper wire (from old electrical cables).
    \item Small piece of cardboard or wood (for a heat-shield handle).
    \item Adhesive tape or thin wire for securing.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Build Steps}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Prepare Copper}: Strip the insulation from the copper wire and straighten it.
    \item \textbf{Creating the Tip}: Wrap one end of the copper wire tightly around the metal wind-guard of the lighter. Ensure it sits directly over the flame exit.
    \item \textbf{Shaping}: Extend the other end of the wire outward and sharpen it slightly with a file to create the soldering tip.
    \item \textbf{Usage}: Ignite the lighter and hold for 30-60 seconds until the tip is hot. Test by touching solder to the tip.
\end{enumerate}

